docs.abstract: James Damore, an engineer who was fired after writing about gender differences, accused the company of workplace discrimination in a lawsuit.
docs.snippet: James Damore, an engineer who was fired after writing about gender differences, accused the company of workplace discrimination in a lawsuit.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — James Damore was  fired from his engineering job at Google last year after he wrote a memo that criticized the company’s diversity efforts and argued that the low number of women in engineering positions was a result of biological differences.

docs.abstract: The authorities have told the popular service Toutiao to clean up salacious material, illustrating the balance required to meet China’s voracious demand.
docs.snippet: The authorities have told the popular service Toutiao to clean up salacious material, illustrating the balance required to meet China’s voracious demand.
docs.lead_paragraph: HONG KONG — One of the world’s most valuable start-ups got that way by using artificial intelligence to satisfy Chinese internet users’ voracious appetite for news and entertainment. Every day, its smartphone app feeds 120 million people personalized streams of buzzy news stories, videos of dogs frolicking in snow, GIFs of traffic mishaps and listicles such as “The World’s Ugliest Celebrities.”

headline.main: A Saucy App Knows China’s Taste in News. The Censors Are Worried.
headline.print_headline: Chinese App  Not as Saucy  After Censors  Have a Say

docs.abstract: A coordinated push by some of the right’s biggest contributors has paved the way for a Supreme Court decision that could cripple public-sector unions.
docs.snippet: A coordinated push by some of the right’s biggest contributors has paved the way for a Supreme Court decision that could cripple public-sector unions.
docs.lead_paragraph: In the summer of 2016, government workers in Illinois received a mailing that offered them tips on how to leave their union. By paying a so-called fair-share fee instead of standard union dues, the mailing said, they would no longer be bound by union rules and could not be punished for refusing to strike.

headline.main: Behind a Key Anti-Labor Case, a Web of Conservative Donors
headline.print_headline: Web of Donors Sees a Chance  To Curb Labor

byline.original: By Noam Scheiber and Kenneth P. Vogel

docs.abstract: The special counsel’s indictment detailed how crucial Facebook and Instagram were to the Russian campaign to disrupt the presidential election.
docs.snippet: The special counsel’s indictment detailed how crucial Facebook and Instagram were to the Russian campaign to disrupt the presidential election.
docs.lead_paragraph: SAN FRANCISCO — In 2014, Russians working for a shadowy firm called the Internet Research Agency started gathering American followers in online groups focused on issues like religion and immigration. Around mid-2015, the Russians began buying digital ads to spread their messages. A year later, they tapped their followers to help organize political rallies across the United States.

headline.main: To Stir Discord in 2016, Russians Turned Most Often to Facebook
headline.print_headline: To Create Rifts, Russians Liked Facebook Most
